You shouldn't need `SFinite Œº` here, as a measure which is absolutely continuous wrt an s-finite measure is itself s-finite, right? (Not sure we have that in mathlib though).

I just proved that and will PR it. The way I did it ended up needing an unexpectedly large amount of stuff about s-finite measures, so that will be several PRs containing the following:
- if a measure `Œº` is s-finite, then `Œº.withDensity f` is s-finite
- any s-finite measure can be written as `withDensity` of a finite measure
- if we have two measures `Œº, ŒΩ` and `ŒΩ` is finite, then `Œº` can be written as a sigma-finite measure plus a measure which is infinite when `ŒΩ` is not zero. Halmos calls the proof technique used here the method of exhaustion.
- putting all of that together: 
```
lemma sFinite_of_absolutelyContinuous {Œº ŒΩ : Measure Œ±} [SFinite ŒΩ] (hŒºŒΩ : Œº ‚â™ ŒΩ) : SFinite Œº
```

That material should also allow us to generalize our Radon-Nikodym theorem.
